04855nam a22007335i 9780674726345DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013955465  a97806747263457 a10.4159/harvard.97806747263452doi  a(DE-B1597)213448  a(OCoLC)979622401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aEDU0340002bisacsh04a370.9173 22231 aBartlett, Lora, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMigrant Teachers :bHow American Schools Import Labor /cLora Bartlett. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (202 p.) :b3 line illustrations, 5 graphs, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tIntroduction and Overview -- tPart one. The Count, Context, and Conditions -- t1 The Scope and Pattern of Overseas Trained Teachers in U.S. Schools -- t2 The Perfect Policy Storm -- tPart two. The Teachers and the Schools -- t3 Transnational Teacher Motivations and Pathways -- t4 Navigating Migration -- t5 A Tale of Two Schools -- tPart three. Implications -- t6 Teachers’ Work -- t7 Transnational Teacher Migration -- tAfterword -- tAppendix. Investigating Teacher Migration -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMigrant Teachers investigates an overlooked trend in U.S. public schools today: the growing reliance on teachers trained overseas, as federal mandates require K-12 schools to employ qualified teachers or risk funding cuts. A narrowly technocratic view of teachers as subject specialists has led districts to look abroad, Lora Bartlett asserts, resulting in transient teaching professionals with little opportunity to connect meaningfully with students. Highly recruited by inner-city school districts that struggle to attract educators, approximately 90,000 teachers from the Philippines, India, and other countries came to the United States between 2002 and 2008. From administrators' perspective, these instructors are excellent employees--well educated and able to teach subjects like math, science, and special education where teachers are in short supply. Despite the additional recruitment of qualified teachers, American schools are failing to reap the possible benefits of the global labor market. Bartlett shows how the framing of these recruited teachers as stopgap, low-status workers cultivates a high-turnover, low-investment workforce that undermines the conditions needed for good teaching and learning. Bartlett calls on schools to provide better support to both overseas-trained teachers and their American counterparts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEducation, UrbanzUnited States. 0aTeachers, ForeignzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067472634540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674726345423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674726345.jpg  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA